		<dc:creator><![CDATA[James Clear]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Mon, 06 May 2013 13:37:06 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://jamesclear-com.uar9g7bv-liquidwebsites.com/?p=4351#comment-961</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[In reply to &lt;a href=&quot;https://jamesclear.com/health-benefits-entrepreneurship#comment-957&quot;&gt;Hong Lee&lt;/a&gt;.

Hong -- thanks for sharing. I&#039;m glad you&#039;re enjoying the articles. I&#039;ll do my best to keep great information coming your way.

As far as becoming an entrepreneur, it&#039;s a tough road (as you already know). That said, I think you can definitely make &lt;em&gt;some version&lt;/em&gt; of your dream a reality. If running a clinic stresses you out to no end, but you want to be working on your own ... then why not build a platform online and see if you can coach and treat your own clients (either virtually or simply use the online platform to drive your client work in the real world). That would drastically reduce overhead and expenses while also giving you the freedom to work on your own.

That&#039;s just one idea. The point here is that you have many options at your disposal for becoming an entrepreneur. They all require hard work, but if you really want to be self&#8211;employed, then there is no reason you can&#039;t do that. I&#039;d spend some time thinking about the different options, brainstorming possible businesses (even if they seem far fetched at first), and considering how you can design your life to provide more fulfillment at work without sacrificing your personal health.

Hope that helps! And, as always, thanks for reading.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>In reply to <a href="https://jamesclear.com/health-benefits-entrepreneurship#comment-957">Hong Lee</a>.</p>
<p>Hong &#8212; thanks for sharing. I&#8217;m glad you&#8217;re enjoying the articles. I&#8217;ll do my best to keep great information coming your way.</p>
<p>As far as becoming an entrepreneur, it&#8217;s a tough road (as you already know). That said, I think you can definitely make <em>some version</em> of your dream a reality. If running a clinic stresses you out to no end, but you want to be working on your own &#8230; then why not build a platform online and see if you can coach and treat your own clients (either virtually or simply use the online platform to drive your client work in the real world). That would drastically reduce overhead and expenses while also giving you the freedom to work on your own.</p>
<p>That&#8217;s just one idea. The point here is that you have many options at your disposal for becoming an entrepreneur. They all require hard work, but if you really want to be self&ndash;employed, then there is no reason you can&#8217;t do that. I&#8217;d spend some time thinking about the different options, brainstorming possible businesses (even if they seem far fetched at first), and considering how you can design your life to provide more fulfillment at work without sacrificing your personal health.</p>
<p>Hope that helps! And, as always, thanks for reading.</p>
