		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://jamesclear-com.uar9g7bv-liquidwebsites.com/?p=4351#comment-957</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[James,

I enjoyed your article on entrepreneurship and health.  I would like to read more articles  on tactics to get started with your own business.  I am a Chiropractor and have had been an entrepreneur in some ways.  In my previous job, I was the clinic director for a brand new clinic with many responsibilities.  Everything from marketing, training, and patient care.  The setup I had was to build up the clinic to where it was producing and I would buy out the investors.  That experience was not healthy for me; I eventually burned out! I invested many hours in getting that clinic up and running.  There were certain factors I had no control over such as the overhead expenses and the billing department which affected my production.  Eventually I decided to leave because my hopes of owning that clinic was gone.  

Now I&#039;m in another job where I just treat patients so I can spend most of my time without the stress of running a business to rebuild my health -- mind, body, and spirit.  I&#039;m loving it, but something inside of my wants to have my own clinic some day.  But, some days I think to myself &quot;Why should I deal with all that stress? Why not just make a decent income, live within my means, and focus on my health and happiness?&quot; 

What are your thoughts? Thanks!]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>James,</p>
<p>I enjoyed your article on entrepreneurship and health.  I would like to read more articles  on tactics to get started with your own business.  I am a Chiropractor and have had been an entrepreneur in some ways.  In my previous job, I was the clinic director for a brand new clinic with many responsibilities.  Everything from marketing, training, and patient care.  The setup I had was to build up the clinic to where it was producing and I would buy out the investors.  That experience was not healthy for me; I eventually burned out! I invested many hours in getting that clinic up and running.  There were certain factors I had no control over such as the overhead expenses and the billing department which affected my production.  Eventually I decided to leave because my hopes of owning that clinic was gone.  </p>
<p>Now I&#8217;m in another job where I just treat patients so I can spend most of my time without the stress of running a business to rebuild my health &#8212; mind, body, and spirit.  I&#8217;m loving it, but something inside of my wants to have my own clinic some day.  But, some days I think to myself &#8220;Why should I deal with all that stress? Why not just make a decent income, live within my means, and focus on my health and happiness?&#8221; </p>
<p>What are your thoughts? Thanks!</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
