		<item>
		<title>
		By: Chitoku Teshima		</title>
		<link>https://jamesclear.com/health-benefits-entrepreneurship#comment-871</link>

		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Chitoku Teshima]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Thu, 25 Apr 2013 05:26:00 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://jamesclear-com.uar9g7bv-liquidwebsites.com/?p=4351#comment-871</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[I have been an entrepreneur in a sense for 3 years or so.  I teach English as a foreign language.  

Basically, there are two different markets for English lessons here in Japan.  One is for students to prepare for college entrance exams.  Students memorizes a lot about English, no matter if that&#039;s practical or not. I am not interested in making them do that.

 The other market is of what they call &quot;conversational&quot; English, which is supposed to be practical.  The teachers on this market are mostly native in English.  I&#039;m not.  Besides, Japanese people believe being native in a language automatically makes you good at teaching the language you speak.  What&#039;s even worse is that those running schools with the native teachers are Japanese who just want to make money, which means the teachers are not paid much. They usually make less than what they need to raise their children, and that forces independent teachers to keep their prices low.

These are the things I learned after I started teaching independently.  Things are very slow in my business.  I don&#039;t believe fighting the ignorance in this local society will do me any good, as it was no good to Buckminster Fuller.  My money doesn&#039;t allow me to advertise my business, either.

Although I still love teaching, and do agree with what you say about being an entrepreneur, I feel I&#039;m lost.  Would you make me any suggestions?]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I have been an entrepreneur in a sense for 3 years or so.  I teach English as a foreign language.  </p>
<p>Basically, there are two different markets for English lessons here in Japan.  One is for students to prepare for college entrance exams.  Students memorizes a lot about English, no matter if that&#8217;s practical or not. I am not interested in making them do that.</p>
<p> The other market is of what they call &#8220;conversational&#8221; English, which is supposed to be practical.  The teachers on this market are mostly native in English.  I&#8217;m not.  Besides, Japanese people believe being native in a language automatically makes you good at teaching the language you speak.  What&#8217;s even worse is that those running schools with the native teachers are Japanese who just want to make money, which means the teachers are not paid much. They usually make less than what they need to raise their children, and that forces independent teachers to keep their prices low.</p>
<p>These are the things I learned after I started teaching independently.  Things are very slow in my business.  I don&#8217;t believe fighting the ignorance in this local society will do me any good, as it was no good to Buckminster Fuller.  My money doesn&#8217;t allow me to advertise my business, either.</p>
<p>Although I still love teaching, and do agree with what you say about being an entrepreneur, I feel I&#8217;m lost.  Would you make me any suggestions?</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
